k?fTi@su64j-qp">x7</variable><variable id="`Qt.3@s[jR:9?KFp9XhI">y4</variable><variable id="%`}p^0=`vCN[s9r5Yu]S">zombieAnimTick</variable><variable id="coIjs.J9]MEwTlSGMt2k">demoPauseUntil2</variable><variable id="-0WovS+Qfd64p{^V}yg/">demoBuildCooldown2</variable><variable type="KIND_SpriteKind" id="(COAb6l|mRk+~WY4d%Hc">Player</variable><variable type="KIND_SpriteKind" id=",Dz+Z+p7/)}Yq(_,-@(,">Projectile</variable><variable type="KIND_SpriteKind" id="Ir_PqwgGdyxPu}K.=SVC">Food</variable><variable type="KIND_SpriteKind" id="eY+mV*Gok*yz!Z!C/OXJ">Enemy</variable></variables><comment id="/cKY74W|H%tnn8+}Ied1" x="0" y="21346" w="480" h="160">
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Tile image generation. The game builds resource and terrain tiles in code so
generated maps can reuse a consistent Minecraft-inspired visual language.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
</comment><comment id="Tf.(y6:rJ.-Boo9E94Zx" x="525" y="21346" w="480" h="160">
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Level theme and music generation. Consecutive levels rotate themes to avoid
repeating the same visual scene and melody style back-to-back.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
</comment><comment id="1~EHsXX7{MM`mtZ)[eP4" x="1050" y="21346" w="480" h="160">
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Demo mode AI. This intentionally stays simple: it is not a perfect solver,
but it demonstrates the core mechanics without player input.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
</comment><comment id="hsHCM503N5`7uistmQFA" x="1575" y="21346" w="480" h="160">
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Render pipeline. A single MakeCode renderable draws the current menu/HUD
layer according to gameState.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
</comment><comment id="[h`ko.Z-zgF4XFfPmzG," x="2100" y="21346" w="480" h="320">
Movement fix: regular player uses PLAYER_SPEED 80; demo remains on DEMO_SPEED 60.
Code review changes in this version
- Resource rendering: resource collection is tile-based, which is correct. I tightened cleanup so it does not accidentally destroy UI helper sprites.
- Tile consistency: the game should use one authoritative setTile() path for harvesting and building. I restored setTile() as the single replacement path and avoided mixed direct tile updates.
- Harvest/build correctness: I normalised the action routine so harvested blocks always become grass and built blocks always spend inventory before replacing the tile.
- Infinite health: I fixed demo/infinite health so zombie collisions still shake and play audio, but do not reduce the life counter.
- Tile rendering: I kept the no-transparent-pixels safeguard but changed initialisation so each tile falls back to its own dominant colour rather than forcing every missing pixel to green.
- Demo movement: diagonal motion previously ran faster than straight-line movement. I added a diagonal speed constant and applied it in demo trajectory movement.
</comment><comment id=",p!lvI(010eOWh@y%4xg" x="2625" y="21346" w="480" h="360">
============================================================================
Minekraft
MakeCode Arcade JavaScript source
Design overview
---------------
Minekraft is a Minecraft-inspired top-down survival and exploration game.
The player moves around a procedurally generated woodland/mining map,
harvests resource tiles, builds simple defensive or traversal blocks,
avoids zombies, and reaches the diamond tile to complete a level.
Core loop
---------
1. Start from the title screen.
2. Configure level count and health in the settings menu.
3. Explore the generated level.
4. Harvest nearby resources with A.
5. Build the currently selected material with A when no harvestable tile
is selected.
6. Use the inventory menu to choose the build material.
7. Survive zombies and reach the diamond.
8. Continue to the next level or show the end-game victory screen.
Demo mode
---------
Demo mode lets the game play itself. The automated player explores,
moves towards the diamond, occasionally harvests nearby resources,
builds simple defensive blocks when needed, and avoids nearby zombies.
During demo play, pressing A or B pauses/resumes the automated player.
</comment><comment id="V};;[,*k!mEGx.[TKJ]p" x="3150" y="21346" w="480" h="360">
Control model
-------------
Normal play:
D-pad  Move player.
Hold A Enter targeting mode. While held, use the D-pad to choose one of
the 8 neighbouring tiles.
Release A Harvest the selected adjacent tile, or build on it.
B      Open inventory.
Inventory menu:
Up/Down Move through available material types.
A       Select highlighted material and close inventory.
B       Close inventory without changing selection.
Collision feedback
------------------
Zombie contact uses camera shake and an impact sound. Player death uses
a separate descending tone sequence before the game-over screen.
</comment><comment id="G=*^lN/g2/#`}6+)^YXt" x="3675" y="21346" w="480" h="360">
Implementation notes
--------------------
The game uses MakeCode Arcade core APIs where practical:
- controller.moveSprite for player movement.
- scene.cameraFollowSprite for camera tracking.
- tiles.createTilemap, tiles.setTileAt and tiles.setWallAt for map logic.
- animation.runImageAnimation for sprite movement frames.
- sprite effects for break, damage, zombie death and diamond marker effects.
- music.playMelody and music.playTone for simple procedural audio.
The tilemap is generated dynamically from a buffer and image layout so that
every level can be different while still using MakeCode Arcade's native wall
and tile collision system.
============================================================================
